  "prompt": "What should I do about my 19-year-old son? He\u2019s serious about a 20-year-old girl in the same class at his university.",
  "response": "It\u2019s great that you\u2019re paying attention to your son\u2019s life and relationships. At 19, your son is at an age where he\u2019s exploring independence and forming meaningful connections. Here are some steps you can take to support him while ensuring he\u2019s making healthy choices:\n\n### 1. **Talk Openly and Respectfully**\n   - Have a calm, non-judgmental conversation with him about his relationship. Show genuine interest in his feelings and experiences.\n   - Avoid being overly critical or dismissive; this could make him defensive or less likely to share with you in the future.\n\n### 2. **Understand the Relationship**\n   - Ask him what he likes about her and how they support each other. Understanding the dynamics of their relationship can help you gauge if it\u2019s healthy and balanced.\n   - Encourage him to share his goals and how the relationship fits into his life.\n\n### 3. **Offer Guidance, Not Control**\n   - Share your wisdom about relationships, such as the importance of mutual respect, communication, and maintaining individual identities.\n   - Avoid dictating what he should or shouldn\u2019t do; instead, help him think critically about his decisions.\n\n### 4. **Encourage Balance**\n   - Remind him to prioritize his education, personal growth, and friendships, alongside his relationship.\n   - Relationships can be all-consuming at this age, so gently encourage him to maintain a well-rounded life.\n\n### 5. **Be a Safe Space**\n   - Let him know you\u2019re there for him if he needs advice or support, whether things go well or not.\n   - Avoid overreacting to minor issues; instead, help him navigate challenges calmly.\n\n### 6. **Respect Their Privacy**\n   - While it\u2019s natural to be curious, avoid prying too much or interfering in their relationship. Trust him to handle it unless there are serious red flags.\n\n### 7. **Address Red Flags**\n   - If you notice signs of an unhealthy relationship (e.g., control, disrespect, or unhealthy dependency), gently raise your concerns. Focus on his well-being rather than blaming the other person.\n\n### 8. **Be Patient**\n   - Relationships at this age are often part of learning and growing. Even if it doesn\u2019t last forever, it can be an important experience for him.\n\n### 9. **Stay Connected**\n   - Maintain a strong, positive relationship with your son. This will make it easier for him to turn to you for advice or support.\n\nUltimately, your role is to guide and support him as he navigates this stage of life. Trust that you\u2019ve raised him well and that he\u2019s capable of making good decisions.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
